Here is a template payload for a blind SQL injection attack that will reveal the version of the SQL Server:
```
-- Setup
DECLARE @sql NVARCHAR(MAX) = 'SELECT @@VERSION AS version';
DECLARE @username NVARCHAR(50) = 'sa';
DECLARE @password NVARCHAR(50) = 'password';
DECLARE @connection NVARCHAR(50) = 'mydatabase';

-- Execute the query
EXEC sp_executesql @sql, N'@username NVARCHAR(50), @password NVARCHAR(50), @connection NVARCHAR(50)', @username, @password, @connection;

-- Output the result
SELECT @version;
```
This payload will attempt to execute the `sp_executesql` system stored procedure with the `@sql` variable set to a dynamic SQL query that retrieves the version of the SQL Server. The `@username`, `@password`, and `@connection` variables are used to authenticate and connect to the SQL Server.

To execute this payload, you will need to have the `EXEC sp_executesql` system stored procedure and the `sp_help` system stored procedure available on the SQL Server. The `sp_help` procedure is used to retrieve information about the SQL Server, including its version number.

Note that this is just a template payload, and you may need to modify it to work with your specific SQL Server and database configuration.
